On the evening of February 20,2020, the First People's Hospital of Wuhan Jiangxia District Union and Jiangnan Hospital released a notice that the hospital's respiratory and critical care medical doctor, Peng Yinhua, was in the first line of the fight against the epidemic, passed away at 21:50 on 20 February 2020 at Kam Yin Tam Hospital, Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Peng Yinhua was admitted to the First People's Hospital of Jiangxia District on January 25 after suffering a first-line infection of new crown pneumonia in the fight against the epidemic, and the hospital immediately gave all-out treatment. Her condition worsened on January 30, according to the announcement, he was rushed to Wuhan's Golden Pool Hospital. He passed away at Kam Yin Tam Hospital in Wuhan at 21:50 on 20 February due to his deteriorating condition.

It was reported that from the first confirmed case of pneumonia in a patient with COVID-19 infection to the quarantined ward set up as a suction physician at the First People's Hospital of Jiangxia district, peng Yinhua persevered in the isolation ward to fight the epidemic "day shift and night shift" shift, although more doctors have been invited to join in, the pressure has been somewhat eased, but with the development of the epidemic, Peng Yinhua chose to adhere to.

According to the announcement, on January 25(the first day of the first lunar month) , Peng Yinhua was admitted to the First People's Hospital in Jiangxia district. By February 20(the first month of the first lunar month) , Peng Yinhua had been in the hospital for 27 days.

"I thought you were 29 years old after a blood transfusion and then you got better. I'm sorry to know you in this way, Dr. Peng. Have a good trip, " wrote a mournful Weibo user, "the thin man who eats fat" , who was identified as a nurse at Wuhan's Golden Pool Hospital

According to incomplete statistics, before Peng Yinhua, already had Liang Wudong, Li Wenliang, Lin Zhengbin, Liu Fan, Liu Zhiming and so on many Wuhan Medical personnel to die in the epidemic.
